Though the crippling nationwide bus strike in South Africa was called off on Monday after workers and employers reached an agreement, some companies said on Tuesday that their operations would not resume immediately In a statement issued shortly before 6am, Gautrain management said that the early morning bus service was not available due to a driver meeting. Buses were dispatched after the meeting. Long-distance coach service providers Greyhound and Citiliner also said that their services resumed on Monday, but all routes would only be fully operational from Wednesday. Reya Vaya, MyCiTi and A Re Yeng – the bus rapid transit systems in Johannesburg, Cape Town and Tshwane respectively – were back in operation on Tuesday. READ MORE: DA calls on KZN Transport MEC to resolve ongoing bus strike Thousands of bus drivers went on strike a month ago, demanding wage increases and better working conditions. On Monday, five unions agreed and signed a new offer, including a nine percent across-the-board wage increase for the first year and eight percent for the second year. – African News Agency